post_text: Over the month of February, the junior and senior classes have been hard at work on ASA’s very own Black History Museum. The project has been a collaborative effort to recognize the impact of African American’s on the history of the United States and remind everyone that African American history is American History.

post_text: We hope everyone had a wonderful Veteran's Day weekend. As we return from the mini break, we wanted to share with you the story of ASA alumni Second Lieutenant Neon Stern. Stern graduates from the Logistics Basic Officer's Leader Course this Thursday and is moving to Fort Campbell, Kentucky where he will be joining the 2nd Brigade Combat Team. We look forward to hearing about everything he accomplishes.

post_text: ASA's guitar department has been busy! Advanced Guitar Ensemble participated in the inaugural Sonoran Desert Guitars' two-day festival at Glendale Community College where they had the opportunity to collaborate and perform with nine other guitar ensembles. On First Friday, guitar ensembles performed at the beautiful Japanese Friendship Garden and played Japanese music, including the traditional folk song "Shabondama". @ Japanese Friendship Garden

post_text: The seniors are currently planning for the All School Retreat on Wednesday, November 20. Retreat is a time where students from all grade levels participate in team building activities in mixed grade level groups. It is a great opportunity for students to feel connected to the larger ASA community. We are asking for donations of individually wrapped candies to distribute as prizes for retreat participants. We hope to time this request to coincide with post Halloween candy sales! Please drop candy donations off in the school office by Monday, November 18. Thanks for your support!

post_text: ASA was honored to participate in the City of Phoenix's 9/11 memorial at City Hall. Thank you for Mr Raetz for the pictures and video. #NeverForget
shared_text:
Jason Raetz is with Heather Lynch-Novak and 2 others.
September 11, 2019 at 5:40 PM ·

So proud of the ASA Chamber Singers as they represented their school masterfully at the City of Phoenix 9/11 memorial at City Hall. They sang Jake Runestad’s Let my Love be Heard and a beautiful arrangement of America the Beautiful. While only one of the singers was born before this tragic event, they performed with amazing poise, reverence and respect. Arizona School for the Arts

Yesterday was the first ever ASA Inclusivity Summit. Based around the TED talk by Chimamanda Adichie “The Danger of a Single Story,” students were exposed to diverse stories of the community around them and engaged in explorations of inclusivity, diversity, and intersectionality.

Thank you to Niamey Thomas, Marcelino Quinones, Eve Aguirre, Mikall Forrester, Yolanda Nussdorfer, and Ayla Owens for sharing your stories, our lives are fuller for hearing them.

post_text: On Sunday morning, about a dozen high schoolers in the Foreign Language Honor Society came to the ASA campus to participate in a campus-wide cleanup! As part of their program, they are committed to giving back to the community by doing a number of service projects. This year, they decided to adopt the ASA neighborhood, and pick-up as much trash as possible from our school site and surrounding areas. It was a huge success, filling bags and buckets with garbage and random debris. Thanks FLHS for giving back to ASA and our community!

post_text: Tomorrow, January 22nd - Come hear the Class of 2019’s personal narratives accompanied by The Sequels, an ASA student band, at Shooflies!
shared_text:
Crescent Ballroom
January 21, 2019 at 1:47 AM ·

This Tuesday, Jan. 22nd - Bar Flies Shoo Flies is in the Ballroom as Arizona School for the Arts high school seniors share their personal slices of life.

Based on Bar Flies, Amy Silverman and Arizona School for the Arts (ASA) faculty Julie Hampton have teamed up to create a public reading to showcase the personal narratives of high school seniors.

6:30pm doors • 7pm show • All ages • $10 available at the door or online here: https://ticketf.ly/2Mka7NN

The last year of high school marks a pivotal transition from dependent child to independent adult and is ripe for reflection on the moments of childhood that made an impact on one's life as one looks ahead to what's next. Hampton's English 12 curriculum encourages students to write personal narratives that demonstrate narrative evidence (setting, dialogue, detailed inventory, gesture, sensory impressions) of a specific moment and narrative distance to suggest what's been discovered about oneself or the world through a writer's lens. The narratives, 500 words or less, demonstrate the courage, humor, and humanity in storytelling.

post_text:
Congrats to Asteroid Belts and Solar Surfers, our middle school robotics teams, who will represent ASA at the State Competition in January! Team Solar Surfers won the Robot Performance Award, scoring the highest in the robot game, as well as the Champion's Award!

Our high school robotics team Voltage also won the design award at their tournament these weekend! It’s competition season, and ASA is on a roll.

Yesterday, members of the cast and crew of ASA’s production of Cabaret got to meet with Alan Cumming, Tony award-winning actor from the 1998 production. What an amazing opportunity!

ASA’s Cabaret runs this weekend, Thursday through Saturday at Phoenix Theatre. Buy your tickets here: tickets.phoenixtheatre.com/single/PSDetail.aspx?psn=10117

post_text:
ASA's Fallapalooza is THIS FRIDAY from 5-8pm on campus!

Some things to keep in mind:
- Games and rides are $1, cash and credit are acceptable.
- Parking is LIMITED, however LYFT rides using the code GOASA will donate a portion of profits to ASA!
- You can purchase ASA gear (including new gear) all night!

Enjoy a night of club fundraising booths, local food trucks, a rock-climbing wall and gaming truck, performances from ASA Jazz Band @5pm and ACTES @6pm, and SO MUCH MORE! See you there! 😄
